    <title>Combined summary - Setting the record straight on Proof-of-Publication</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T14:49:28.385409+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-December/006985.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In email exchanges regarding Bitcoin, multiple topics are discussed including the preservation of scarcity and innovation within the cryptocurrency. The debate centers on 1-way-peg versus 2-way-peg mechanisms and objections to creating new artificial scarcity races while innovating. Additionally, the conversation delves into proof-of-publication as a solution to the double-spend problem. This system uses cryptographic methods such as timestamping, proof-of-receipt, proof-of-non-publication, and proof-of-membership. There are also debates on mechanisms for detecting divergence in embedded consensus systems, with one individual offering several possibilities such as transactions containing a hash of the previous consensus state and using state hashes as encryption keys. Furthermore, the importance of making robust arguments and arguing against the strongest opposing position known is emphasized, as well as the principle of charity when interpreting an argument.Proof-of-publication is a concept gaining attention in the embedded consensus systems and sidechains model proposed by Blockstream. The system uses cryptographic methods such as timestamping, proof-of-receipt, proof-of-non-publication, and proof-of-membership to solve the double-spend problem, and has many practical applications. However, some common myths about proof-of-publication need to be debunked, such as confusing it with timestamping, assuming it is always easy to censor, and believing it cannot be made expensive.The use of proof-of-publication systems in Bitcoin can have varying effects on the cryptocurrency's price, depending on whether the uses are related to money or not. One benefit of proof-of-publication is that it provides a useful solution to the double-spend problem and does not bloat the blockchain. However, the inefficiency of global consensus is a fundamental problem with Bitcoin's architecture that applies to all uses of it.There is a debate regarding the security of client-side validation versus SPV, with some arguing that the former is mathematically secure while the latter is economically secure. However, the comparison is fallacious since the alternative to a proof-of-publication system reliant on client-side validation is a blockchain. In an email conversation between odinn and Peter Todd, odinn expressed his belief that Todd was falling into the trap of dismissing certain ideas as inefficient or "scamcoin" without proper consideration. Todd responded by stating that he prefers to make robust arguments, even if he accepts that 95% of what his opponents say is true.</summary>
